children.subject: There’s an option when you enroll for the grading. My advisor suggested I could do that so that I can focus more on CS classes
If you're looking to declare CS, you shouldn't PNP a major requirement. 70 with 61a is possible, but do expect a really heavy workload.
Why/how would you P/NP 16A, out of curiosity?

I recommend you to take ee16A + 61A + 70 by assuming that you already took LA, circuits, discrete math, and data structures in community college. It will be brutal even though you took all those classes, which is from my experience. If you didn't, don't take 3 techs. You'll end up doing worse and worse in future classes like dominoes. Also, don't to PNP for 16A. You will miss out a lot for future classes if you choose to skip this. It's different from CC here, so don't expect to skim through the materials and learn them. Try not to finish everything so fast so you can optimize your upper div classes. If you do so, it'll just put you in a worse position. So as a transfer, try to start slow as much as possible.

history.content:
For my first semester as a CS intended junior transfer, I’m not sure which would be the best route to go. Has anyone taken CS 61A and EE 16A along with any of the following : 61B/61C/70. 
I do want to finish my lower division pre reqs by the second semester. For that, my next semester would have CS 61C, CS 70, and EE 16B. 

Would it be recommended to take CS 70 now with CS 61A and EE 16A and then CS 61B/47B, CS 61C, EE 16B in the next semester or some other schedule would be better? Thanks.

Also, has anyone taken CS 70 along with 61A?
